Anyway, a related topic is be thoughtful and respectful about how you judge people’s experience. You can ask them, like “hey I don’t want to assume anything, could you give me a summary of your experience in AWS?” before you get into a walkthrough of your architecture.

Helping your teammates grow, whoever they are, means you have people who can second guess you, contribute alternative solutions when you’re stuck, make suggestions in meetings or PRs, help put out a fire. And you can do the same for them. Why do it alone?
Colleagues aren’t fungible ticket completers. Don’t toss a ticket over the wall and then wait for a PR. This is even more important when working remote where it’s easier to remain isolated.
We have onboarding docs going over the important documentation, repos and development practices. We use the word “we” as much as possible and avoid blame games.

I make it really clear that they aren’t expected to remember everything and that some of these systems have gotchas or require a certain way of thinking and they’ll be easier to understand once they’ve had hands on experience.

Some things that have helped at my current company:
New people get assigned a different buddy every week until they’ve met and worked with everyone on the team. I’ve encouraged them to keep reaching out to me if they have questions. I will occasionally check in with them.

Our reliance on JS/TS at my job is honestly the most likely thing that would make me leave. It’s not terrible but I can’t see myself using it for the rest of my life.

Typescript is great but it’s definitely bolted on and is more complex than a language with native types. The lack of runtime type information is rough. More than a few times I start designing something in my head before I remember I don’t have types at runtime.
This took much longer than necessary because there are a zillion different libraries that kinda do what I needed but not perfectly. I glued together 2 or 3 libraries out of the ~dozen I considered.

This is legit one of the coolest things I’ve ever built. I might be able to build on this to unit test, or integration test, that the OpenAPI paths we define actually exist too, in case we typo paths in the lambda.
This has taken two weeks but I think it’s worth it because all we have to care about now is the spec and running the script, then calling the validator function in our code. It’s super decoupled.
All you have to do is make a change to the spec and run a build script and it generates everything. This wouldn’t be necessary in other languages like Java but whatever, this is what we’re using.

We want to specify the exact schema to use in validation so we aren’t doing more work than necessary since it’s a lambda, so I even got type checking on the string for the schema name using template literal types. You can’t typo the schema name.

I have finally finished making an OpenAPI spec the single source of truth in our Typescript based API. It generates Typescript types, AJV uses the schemas inside the spec for runtime validation and the validation properly narrows the type after.

So you'd write the dialogue for NPCs, dialogue options for players. That then gets passed to the "director layer" where the characters are scheduled to go to the location and provide the option to start the conversation.

This is passed to the "scenario writer" layer which makes queries into a Tracery-esque corpus where all the dialogue segments are tagged to hell. This character is worried but brash and trusts who they're talking to, select brusque greeting, embarrassed worried statement.

A flood could trigger a "worried conversation" story shape. the next system is the "pick and place" layer, take the story shape and start finding characters to participate in the conversation, the location, etc and plugs them into the story shape.

I'd like to build this system in layers. the "story shape" layer is where I write the structure of different kinds of conversations. after an in-game event fires the World System selects various story shapes that would fit with the event.

The Isekai/portal fantasy genre is very saturated. It moves and evolves fast as stories try to differentiate themselves. For a very long time it was not a genre I really cared for, but in the last couple of years the variants have become quite interesting to me.

Last night after I caught up with one Webtoon I was recommended another one that's new and read through all 10 chapters in one go. It's called The Fabled Warrior and it's about a mom decades after she had returned home from going to another world to save it. It fucking rules.
God, we are so lucky to be living now in a time where there are so many stories out there. Manhwas/webtoons/manga/webcomics/light novels/books/short stories. What a feast.

I'm gonna keep trying out webnovels cuz I'm vaguely interested in writing one and I want to see how they tick, but even if I can't find one that really hooks me at least I have manhwas/webtoons to reference and be motivated by their excellence.

Just like with ideas for games, apps, business, whatever, the execution of a story idea is what matters most. Not only because bad execution ruins the idea, but because it's the execution that is actually the engrossing thing to experience. An idea is a sliver of the reality.

You can even spoil the damn story and have it work. Doom Breaker tells you the overarching endgoal of the protag in the 1st chapter but what matters is I want to see it happen myself. You're damn right I want to see the strongest human fighter get a second chance at killing God.

If my imagination starts coming up with possible storylines and I am really on board for those storylines then I'm hooked. And I don't have to be right. If the actual storylines are compatible with my expectations then we're still good!

If a protag takes an action to make me think "this is a cornerstone of who they are that will inform everything about how they will behave" and the obstacle makes me think "this is a cornerstone of how the world/antagonist works", I'll be thinking what happens when they collide.

I'm gonna keep looking but so far there has been too much world building too early. Too much backstory, filling out the protag. All I need is a character action taken against an obstacle, and have those things be as pure and undiluted as possible to set my imagination ablaze.

It's an interesting juxtaposition because manhwas and manga are a massive and obvious influence on popular webnovels/serialized stories these days. The story premises, tropes, and covers all draw from them, but I'm still looking for stories that have powerful hooks.
